title: For Sale/Trade:  Yugo SKS  & accessories
postcontent: Yugoslavian SKS, made sometime in the 1960's if I had to guess from quality. All parts numbers matching, but it's been fucked by california (launcher brake removed and thrown away, replaced and welded down by a replacement brake, launching sight cut off) so it doesn't really have that much collectible value. Bought during the rush for 700, I know I won't get that back but I kinda want to at least try to break even. The stock has quite a lot of cosmoline residue and though I sweated the stock last summer it's only marginally acceptable, so you might want to do a 922r conversion and use the tapco stock I'm including with it so you don't have to deal with the ickiness of the original stock. Not looking to break up the deal, what you see is what you buy. The outside of the gun and the blued finish is rough and faded, but judging by the quality of the bore (it's very clean) this was likely a guard's gun that was often carried and abused but seldom fired. despite the mushy SKS trigger it's a tack driver at 200 yards, never jammed on me once, internals are also imacculate.comes with 15 EXCELLENT QUALITY clips, selected from the best of about eighty other clips as the ones that are least likely to jam.some triple-compartmented pouch, unsure of the origin. can hold all 15 loaded clips at once.tapco stock. planned to do a 922r conversion so I could legally put it on the gun but never went through with it.an ak/sks cleaning kit.650 buys all.

title: For Sale:  Ljungman AG 42b rifle
postcontent:
Pristine Ljungman AG 42b rifle.With bayonet . extra Sights, cleaning kit.and tool kit. extra magazine,springs ,firing pin. ext.this rifle is in excellent condition. see pictures. thanks.
The Ag m/42 was designed by Erik Eklund of the AB C.J. Ljungmans Verkstäder company of Malmö around 1941, and entered production at the Carl Gustafs Stads Gevärsfaktori in Eskilstuna in 1942. Some 30,000 rifles were manufactured in all for the Swedish Army. This was a relatively small number of weapons and the standard infantry rifle remained the 6.5 mm bolt-action m/96 Mauser.
After a number of issues had been discovered, including a serious problem with rusting gas tubes, the existing stocks of the rifle were modified between 1953 and 1956, and the reworked rifles were designated Ag m/42B. Modifications included a stainless steel gas tube, two knobs on the breech cover, a new elevation knob for the rear sight, a rubber case-deflector, new magazines and new cleaning rod. The Ag m/42B was replaced in Swedish service in the mid 1960s by the Ak 4 (derived from the Heckler & Koch G3).
